## Manufacturing Procedures {#sec-manufacturing}

## 3D Printing Guide {#sec-3d-printing}

All plastic components are designed for FDM 3D printing with specific settings optimized for thread quality and structural integrity. PETG or ASA material is required for impact resistance and UV stability. Critical: threads require post-processing with tap and die tools.

::: {.cell fig-height='6' fig-width='10' execution_count=11}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Tool requirements for probe assembly including thread cutting tools (M12x1.75 tap and die), assembly supplies (epoxy, heat shrink), and finishing tools. 3D printer settings shown for Bambu Lab / FDM machines.](mechanical_files/figure-pdf/fig-tool-requirements-output-1.png){#fig-tool-requirements}
:::
:::


| Setting | Value | Notes |
|---------|-------|-------|
| Material | PETG or ASA | Required for impact/UV |
| Layer Height | 0.12mm (Target) | Critical for threads |
| Infill | 100% (Solid) (Target) | Critical for strength |
| Walls | 6 Loops (Target) | Solid threaded regions |
| Supports | DISABLED | Use built-in scaffolding |
| Speed | 50mm/s (Target) outer wall | Quality over speed |

: Recommended 3D printer settings for probe components. {#tbl-print-settings}

## Thread Post-Processing {#sec-thread-postprocessing}

::: {.callout-note}
## Thread Cutting Procedure

- Male threads: Print at 12.2mm OD (Target), cut with M12x1.75 Die
- Female threads: Print at 10.5mm hole (Target), cut with M12x1.75 Tap
- Always use cutting oil to reduce friction
- Cut slowly, back out frequently to clear chips
- Test fit before epoxy assembly
:::

## Insertion Methods {#sec-mech-insertion-methods}

Four primary insertion methods accommodate different soil conditions. Method selection depends on soil type, target depth, and available equipment. The pilot rod method requires complete removal of metal before measurements.

::: {.cell fig-height='8' fig-width='10' execution_count=12}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Probe insertion methods: (a) Hand auger for most soils using 10-20mm (Target) auger; (b) Pilot rod for compact soils - must remove metal before survey; (c) Direct push in sandy soils only; (d) Water-jet method for excellent sand penetration with minimal disturbance.](mechanical_files/figure-pdf/fig-insertion-methods-output-1.png){#fig-insertion-methods}
:::
:::


## Assembly Sequence {#sec-assembly-sequence}

Probe assembly follows a bottom-to-top sequence with all components screwing together via M12 threads. The modular design enables field assembly and allows replacement of individual segments without rebuilding the entire probe.

::: {.cell fig-height='10' fig-width='7' execution_count=13}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Assembly sequence from bottom to top: (1) Probe tip pointing down, (2) Bottom rod segment with RX coil, (3) First ERT ring at 0.5m (Target), (4) Coupler joint, (5) Top rod segment with TX coil, (6) Additional ERT rings, (7) Junction box at surface level.](mechanical_files/figure-pdf/fig-assembly-sequence-output-1.png){#fig-assembly-sequence}
:::
:::


## Advantages of Micro-Probe Design {#sec-mech-advantages}

::: {.cell fig-height='7' fig-width='10' execution_count=14}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Summary of micro-probe design advantages including 10x (Modeled) less disturbance, modular field-serviceable construction, passive probes with no downhole electronics, and 70% (Modeled) cost reduction compared to traditional designs.](mechanical_files/figure-pdf/fig-advantages-output-1.png){#fig-advantages}
:::
:::


Key advantages of the micro-probe design include:

- **Strength:** 16mm OD (Target) allows for robust M12 threads
- **Modularity:** Sensor spacing determined by rod segment length
- **Manufacturability:** Sensors built into printed parts, not glued onto rod
- **Smooth Profile:** Flush connections prevent snagging during insertion/extraction
- **Field Serviceable:** Replace individual segments without rebuilding entire probe
- **Simpler Assembly:** No electronics in probe
- **Lighter Weight:** ~50-100 g per meter (Modeled) (vs 200-250 g)
- **Easier Insertion:** Smaller diameter, less force needed
- **Lower Cost:** ~$40-60 per probe (Target) (vs $130-180)
- **Better Reliability:** Passive probes more robust
- **Minimal Intrusion:** ~10x (Modeled) less disturbance than 25mm design

## Rapid Prototyping Guide {#sec-rapid-prototyping}

This section provides a streamlined workflow for building a **Minimum Viable Prototype (MVP)** to validate the probe design quickly. The goal is to achieve first functional data within 1-2 days, enabling rapid iteration if design changes are needed.

### Prototyping Philosophy {#sec-proto-philosophy}

The prototyping approach follows a "fail-fast" methodology:

- **Prioritize speed to first data** over production quality
- **Use relaxed tolerances** (+/-20% (Target) vs +/-10% (Target)) for initial validation
- **Accept reversible assembly** (dry-fit, no epoxy) for iteration
- **Focus on core physics validation** before manufacturing refinement

::: {.callout-tip}
## MVP Success Criteria (Relaxed for Prototyping)

| Parameter | Production Spec | Prototype Target |
|-----------|-----------------|------------------|
| Inductance | 1.5 mH +/-10% (Target) | 1.5 mH +/-20% (Target) |
| Q Factor @ 10kHz | >=30 (Target) | >=15 (Target) |
| Metal detection | Calibrated | Visible response |
| Thread quality | Production | Functional fit |

If these relaxed criteria are met, proceed to production-quality builds.
:::

### Prototyping Workflow {#sec-proto-workflow}

The MVP build process consists of four main phases that can be completed in approximately 10-12 hours of active work over 2 days.

