### Coil Winding for Prototyping {#sec-proto-coil}

The coil is the most critical component. Follow this simplified winding procedure optimized for first-time success.

::: {.cell fig-height='4' fig-width='10' execution_count=16}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Step-by-step coil winding visual guide. The process takes 45-90 minutes (Target) depending on experience. Key success factors: consistent tension, close-wound turns, and measurement before securing.](mechanical_files/figure-pdf/fig-coil-winding-steps-output-1.png){#fig-coil-winding-steps}
:::
:::


**Coil Winding Checklist:**

1. [ ] Clean ferrite rod with IPA
2. [ ] Mark 50mm (Target) winding zone at center
3. [ ] Leave 150mm (Target) wire tail, secure with tape
4. [ ] Wind 300 turns (Target), single layer, close-wound
5. [ ] Maintain consistent light tension (~50g (Target))
6. [ ] **Measure inductance before securing** (target: 1.2-1.8 mH (Target))
7. [ ] Apply thin CA glue or nail polish to fix
8. [ ] Strip and tin wire ends (5mm (Target))

::: {.callout-warning}
## Critical: Measure Before Securing

Always verify inductance *before* applying fixative. If inductance is outside 1.2-1.8 mH (Target), adjust turns (+/-20-30 turns) and re-measure. Once glue is applied, changes are difficult.
:::

### Quick Functional Test Setup {#sec-proto-test-setup}

The functional test validates that the coil responds to conductive targets. This is a qualitative "go/no-go" test before proceeding to full calibration.

::: {.cell fig-height='5' fig-width='10' execution_count=17}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Bench test setup for functional validation. A function generator drives the coil at 10 kHz (Target) through a 100 ohm (Target) current-limiting resistor. The oscilloscope monitors the coil voltage. When a metal target approaches, the amplitude and/or phase should change visibly.](mechanical_files/figure-pdf/fig-quick-test-setup-output-1.png){#fig-quick-test-setup}
:::
:::


**Test Procedure:**

1. Connect function generator to coil through 100 ohm (Target) series resistor
2. Set generator to 10 kHz (Target) sine wave, 2V peak-to-peak (Target)
3. Connect oscilloscope across the coil
4. Record baseline amplitude (no target present)
5. Slowly approach metal target (bolt, aluminum can) on non-metallic stick
6. Watch for amplitude or phase change on oscilloscope
7. Note distance at which change becomes visible

**Pass Criteria:**

- Stable baseline signal
- Visible change when metal target within 10cm (Target)
- Response repeatable across 3 trials

### Prototype Test Decision Tree {#sec-proto-decision}

After completing the functional test, use this decision tree to determine next steps.

::: {.cell fig-height='6' fig-width='10' execution_count=18}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display}
![Decision tree for prototype test results. Each test checkpoint has a clear pass/fail criterion with corresponding remediation action. All three tests must pass to proceed to Phase 2 (add ERT, multi-segment assembly).](mechanical_files/figure-pdf/fig-proto-decision-output-1.png){#fig-proto-decision}
:::
:::


| Test | Pass Criteria | If Fail |
|------|---------------|---------|
| Coil L, Q | L = 1.2-1.8 mH (Target), Q >= 15 (Target) | Re-wind coil, check core |
| Thread fit | Parts screw together | Reprint with blanks + tap/die |
| Metal detect | Visible response | Debug test setup, check drive |

